What is the greatest prime factor of $12!+ 14!$?(Reminder: If $n$ is a positive integer, then $n!$ stands for the product $1\cdot 2\cdot 3\cdot \cdots \cdot (n-1)\cdot n$.)
Next, we can consider the expression $14!$. Since $14! = 14 \times 13 \times 12!$, we can factor out $12!$ from the expression to get $14! = 14 \times 13 \times 12!$. Substituting the prime factorization of $12!$ in, we have $14! = 14 \times 13 \times 2^{10} \times 3^5 \times 5^2 \times 7 \times 11$.
solution: Factor out $12!$ from both terms: $12!+14!=12!(1+13\cdot 14)=12!\cdot 183$.  Factor $183=3\cdot 61$.  Since $12!$ has no prime factors greater than 11, $\boxed{61}$ is the greatest prime factor of $12!+14!$.
gpt_response: Now we can add $12!$ and $14!$ to get $12!+14! = 2^{10} \times 3^5 \times 5^2 \times 7 \times 11 \times 13 + 2^{10} \times 3^5 \times 5^2 \times 7 \times 11 \times 13 \times 14$. Factoring out the common factors, we get $12!+14! = 2^{10} \times 3^5 \times 5^2 \times 7 \times 11 \times (1 + 14)$. Simplifying further, we get $12!+14! = 2^{10} \times 3^5 \times 5^2 \times 7 \times 11 \times 15 = 2^{10} \times 3^5 \times 5^2 \times 7 \times 11 \times 3 \times 5$. The greatest prime factor of $12!+14!$ is $\boxed{11}$.
